{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}} {{Use British English|date=March 2016}} {{Infobox cricketer | name = Tim Coleman | image = | country = England | fullname = Tim Coleman | nickname = | birth_date = c.1700 | birth_place = [[England]] | batting = unknown hand | bowling = underarm: unknown hand and type | role = player | club1 = [[London Cricket Club]] | year1 = c.1720-1740 | club2 = [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]] | year2 = c.1720-1740 | date = 10 August | year = 2008 | columns = 0 | source = [[H T Waghorn]] }}
'''Tim Coleman''' (dates unknown) was an early English [[cricket]]er who played for [[London Cricket Club]] and [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]] during the 1720s and 1730s.
==Career== Coleman is one of the earliest cricketers whose name has survived in contemporary records. In 1731, a newspaper report of a match at [[Mitcham Cricket Green]] on Saturday 2 October refers to him as "the famous Tim Coleman".<ref name=DC>[[H T Waghorn]], ''The Dawn of Cricket'', Electric Press, 1906</ref>
The full span of his career is unknown but he must have established his reputation during the 1720s when the London club is known to have played several matches. London was the dominant team in English cricket through the 1730s.<ref name=LL>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110629140105/http://www.jl.sl.btinternet.co.uk/stampsite/cricket/ladstolords/1731.html#coleman From Lads to Lord's – Tim Coleman]</ref>
